Note:
This file handles tail call optimization (TCO) for MIR.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Identify calls in tail position (a CALL/CALL_INDIRECT whose result flows
  directly into the function's RETURN with no intervening computation)
- Stamp the canonical is_tail_call flag (MIRCall extended offset 120) on each
  confirmed tail call

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- The LIR layer consumes the is_tail_call flag for jmp-vs-call selection,
  enabling constant-stack-space tail recursion and reuse of the caller frame
- Functional programming patterns rely on tail-call elimination to avoid stack
  overflow in deep recursion

DESIGN NOTE (canonical contract, matches transformations/optimization.runa
optimize_tail_calls):
A previous revision attempted a bespoke self-recursion-to-loop rewrite that
deleted the call+return and jumped to the entry block WITHOUT rebinding the
call's arguments to the function's parameters. Under the canonical lowering
contract, parameters are materialized through allocas rather than the
MIRFunction parameter value-id List, so a sound MIR-level argument rebinding
has no parameter value ids to target. The complete and correct mechanism is to
stamp the canonical flag and let the LIR tail-call lowering own argument
placement and the actual jump emission — which is sound for self-recursive and
cross-function tail calls alike.

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- Tail-position detection over the canonical instruction stream
- is_tail_call flag stamping
- Per-function and per-program drivers
:End Note

Note: ============================================================
Note: IMPORTS
Note: ============================================================
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir.runa" as MIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir_nodes.runa" as MIRNodes
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/cfg.runa" as CFG
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================
Note: TAIL CALL IDENTIFICATION + STAMPING
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
Tail-position detection works on the canonical block instruction stream. A call
is in tail position when the block ends with the pattern
    ... ; <call> ; <return>
where <call> is MIR_CALL (20304) or MIR_CALL_INDIRECT (20305), <return> is
MIR_RETURN (20303), and the return's returned value-id equals the call's result
value-id. The both-zero case (void call followed by void return) is also a tail
call: a void call has result value-id 0 and a void return carries returned
value-id 0, so the equality test admits it.

WHY THE LAST-TWO-INSTRUCTIONS SHAPE:
After SSA construction and CFG normalization, a return that consumes a call
result sits immediately after the call in the same block; there is no
intervening computation on the result by definition of tail position. We do not
chase single-successor jump chains because the MIR builder collapses trivial
branch chains, so the in-block shape captures the realistic patterns while the
predicate stays O(1) per block.

WHY WE SKIP ALREADY-STAMPED CALLS:
The O3 pipeline runs passes to a fixpoint. Re-counting an already-stamped tail
call would keep the "changed" flag set forever and prevent convergence, so a
call whose flag is already 1 is not recounted.

WHY CONSERVATIVE:
A false positive would let a non-tail call be lowered as a jump and corrupt the
caller's stack frame, so every uncertain path declines to stamp.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Scans every block of the CFG and stamps is_tail_call on every confirmed tail
call. Returns the number of newly-stamped tail calls.
@End Implementation
Process called "stamp_tail_calls" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let blocks be proc get_mir_cfg_blocks from CFG with cfg_ptr
    If blocks is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let block_count be proc length from List with blocks
    Let stamped be 0
    Let block_idx be 0

    While block_idx is less than block_count:
        Let block_ptr be proc list_get from List with blocks, block_idx
        If block_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with block_ptr
            If instructions is not equal to 0:
                Let inst_count be proc length from List with instructions
                If inst_count is greater than or equal to 2:
                    Let call_inst be proc list_get from List with instructions, inst_count minus 2
                    Let ret_inst be proc list_get from List with instructions, inst_count minus 1

                    If call_inst is not equal to 0 and ret_inst is not equal to 0:
                        Let call_opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with call_inst
                        Let ret_opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with ret_inst

                        Let is_call be 0
                        If call_opcode is equal to 20304:  Note: MIR_CALL
                            Set is_call to 1
                        End If
                        If call_opcode is equal to 20305:  Note: MIR_CALL_INDIRECT
                            Set is_call to 1
                        End If

                        If is_call is equal to 1:
                            If ret_opcode is equal to 20303:  Note: MIR_RETURN
                                Let call_result be proc get_mir_node_value_id from MIR with call_inst
                                Let ret_value be proc get_return_value from MIRNodes with ret_inst

                                If call_result is equal to ret_value:
                                    Let already_tail be proc is_tail_call from MIRNodes with call_inst
                                    If already_tail is equal to 0:
                                        Note: Stamp the canonical is_tail_call flag at the
                                        Note: MIRCall extended offset 120 (OD-1 prefix
                                        Note: embedding) for the LIR jmp-vs-call selector.
                                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with call_inst, 120, 1
                                        Set stamped to stamped plus 1
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set block_idx to block_idx plus 1
    End While

    Return stamped
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: MAIN ENTRY POINTS
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
Per-function driver. mir_optimizer.optimize_tail_call dispatches here with the
MIRFunction pointer (extracted from OptimizerContext offset 8). External
functions have no body to analyze; the CFG fetch returns 0 for them and we
decline. Returns 1 only when at least one tail call was newly stamped so the
optimizer pipeline's change predicate observes real progress and the O3
fixpoint converges.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
Identifies and stamps tail calls in a single function. Returns 1 if any tail
call was newly stamped, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation
Process called "optimize_function_with_tail_call" that takes function_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If function_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cfg_ptr be proc get_mir_function_cfg from MIR with function_ptr
    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let stamped be proc stamp_tail_calls with cfg_ptr

    If stamped is greater than 0:
        Let stamped_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with stamped
        Display "Tail call optimization stamped tail call sites: " joined with stamped_str
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Program-level driver. Applies the per-function pass across the MIR module,
skipping external (declared-but-not-defined) functions. The pass is non-fatal:
a per-function decline does not abort the program walk, because tail-call
stamping is profitable but not load-bearing for correctness.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
Runs tail call optimization across every non-external function of a MIRProgram.
Returns 1 on success.
@End Implementation
Process called "run_tail_call_pass" that takes program_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If program_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let functions be proc get_program_functions from MIRNodes with program_ptr
    If functions is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let func_count be proc length from List with functions
    Let optimized_count be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than func_count:
        Let func_ptr be proc list_get from List with functions, i
        If func_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Let is_external be proc is_external_function from MIR with func_ptr
            If is_external is equal to 0:
                Let changed be proc optimize_function_with_tail_call with func_ptr
                If changed is equal to 1:
                    Set optimized_count to optimized_count plus 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Profitability gate. Tail-call stamping changes debuggability (a recursive frame
chain becomes a single iterating frame at the LIR layer), so it is enabled at
-O1 and above and disabled at -O0 to preserve the source-level call shape for
step-debugging. The only further signal needed is "does this function contain a
call?": with no call there is nothing to stamp.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
Returns 1 if the pass should run for this function at this optimization level,
0 otherwise.
@End Implementation
Process called "should_run_tail_call" that takes function_ptr as Integer, optimization_level as Integer returns Integer:
    If optimization_level is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If function_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let call_count be proc count_instructions_of_type from MIRNodes with function_ptr, 20304
    If call_count is greater than 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let indirect_count be proc count_instructions_of_type from MIRNodes with function_ptr, 20305
    If indirect_count is greater than 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: PASS METADATA
Note: ============================================================

@Implementation
Returns the pass name string pointer.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_tail_call_pass_name" returns Integer:
    Return "Tail Call Optimization"
End Process

@Implementation
Returns the pass description string pointer.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_tail_call_pass_description" returns Integer:
    Return "Stamps calls in tail position with the canonical is_tail_call flag for LIR jmp-vs-call selection"
End Process
